# Markdown Link Standards

## Link Format

All internal links use standard Markdown link syntax:

```markdown
[Link Text](path/to/file.md)
```

## Relative Paths

- Use relative paths from the document location.
- Use `../` to navigate up (e.g. from `docs/conceptual/` to `docs/strategic/`).
- Same-directory: `[ConOps](conops.md)` or `[PRD](prd-lean.md)`.

## DocForge-Specific Examples

### Same directory (e.g. in `docs/conceptual/`)
```markdown
[ConOps](conops.md)
[PRD (Lean)](prd-lean.md)
```

### Parent directory (e.g. from `docs/conceptual/` to strategic)
```markdown
[Solution Concept](../strategic/solution-concept.md)
```

### Sibling or other layer (e.g. from `docs/conceptual/` to architectural)
```markdown
[High-Level Architecture](../architectural/hla.md)
[ADR Log](../architectural/adrs/README.md)
```

### Root
```markdown
[README](../../README.md)
```

## Link Types

- **Internal**: Link to other Markdown files; use descriptive link text; include `.md` extension.
- **Section anchors**: `[Section Name](#section-name)` (headings become lowercase, spaces to hyphens).
- **External**: Full URLs: `[Link Text](https://example.com)`.

## Prohibited

- Backtick-only references: `` `file.md` `` (use a proper link).
- Bare paths without brackets: `file.md` (use `[description](file.md)`).

## Document Graph and Navigation

- Each doc should be reachable via links from README or from other docs in its layer.
- End documents with navigation: *Previous: [Upstream](path) Â· Next: [Downstream](path)* (see docforge-drafter).
- Frontmatter `depends_on` lists upstream documents read for drafting; use it for traceability, not as a substitute for in-body links.
